1.3.4	The former would point toward RAM / processor preformance.	St
1.3.5	Hard-drive speed mainly dictates the latter.	St
1.3.6	To decide if your program is ram-starved, lets try this.	St
1.3.7	Before opening your Nikon software, pull up your task manager.	St
1.3.8	You can get this by right clicking on your taskbar and selecting 'task manager'.	St
1.3.9	Go to the performance tab and write down the number next to Available Physical Memory.	St
1.3.10	Now open up the Nikon software and note the available memory again.	St
1.3.11	Try opening an image and note this number a final time.	St
1.3.12	You will want a few hundred MBs of ram available or your preformance will fall off drastically as your system starts to swap memory to and from the hard-drive.	St
1.3.13	Feel free to post your numbers back here for review.	St
1.3.14	1GB of ram might be plenty of ram if most of it is free, but if you have several other programs and background processes running, it may not be enough.	St
1.3.15	As far as adding a new hard drive, this will not improve your performance much, unless your current disk is a dinosaur.	St
1.3.16	Adding RAM might be a good step, but it would be worthwhile to check your numbers before going out to make the purchase.	St
