1.5.1	You have more than 300MB free RAM after loading the program and opening a NEF file.	St
1.5.2	That looks good, and I doubt you will see any improvement by adding another gig.	St
1.5.3	The two possible bottlenecks for saving files are processor speed and hard-drive speed.	St
1.5.4	As you might be aware the Nikon NF software doesn't apply the edits to the original file, but saves the edits seperate, keeping the original file intact.	St
1.5.5	This is great in that the original file is undisturbed, but not so great in that a file with several edits becomes a resource hog.	St
1.5.6	Defragging your drive can't hurt, but again you can do a simple test to see which is likely slowing your system the most.	St
1.5.7	In task manager if you click the preformance tab, you can watch your CPU usage while saving a file.	St
1.5.8	If it goes to 100% and stays there for the majority of your wait, you can assume that the processor is the bottleneck.	St
1.5.9	If it stays considerably lower than 100 for the duration of the save, you can assume that your hard-drive speed is to blame.	St
1.5.10	If you need quicker disk-access, your best bet is two SATA disks configured in a RAID-0 configuration.	St
1.5.11	If the processor speed is the bottleneck, then an upgrade to P4 3.0E for about 90 dollars would be your best option.	St
1.5.12	Neither of these is quite as easy as plugging in some more ram, but if you're up to it, there is still some more preformance hidden away in your box.	St
